"""
mkt-context: Psalms 147-150
Chapters: 147-150 (49 verses — Psalter closing doxological sequence)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-147-150.py

Key context decisions:
- Ps 147: Three movements (vv1,7,12); stars-named vs. brokenhearted-healed juxtaposition;
  word running swiftly (v15) connects to creation-word/Torah-word/John 1 trajectory;
  closes with covenant particularity after universal creation praise
- Ps 148: Two sweeps (heavenly vv1-6, earthly vv7-12); sea monsters (tanninim) as
  praisers subverts ANE chaos-mythology; covenant particularity at end (v14)
- Ps 149: Paradox of praise + two-edged sword; neqamah-warfare reframed in NT as
  spiritual warfare (Eph 6); chasidim identity central
- Ps 150: Grand Doxology; 7 instruments named; neshamah back to Gen 2:7;
  Paul quotes cymbal image in 1 Cor 13:1 (negatively)
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge without overwriting any verse already present in existing
    # CHANGE? Do not alter the guard; concurrent agents depend on append-only behavior
    # VERIFY: run twice; second run should report identical byte count for psalms.json
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {"147": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 147: Triple-Movement Praise Psalm — YHWH's Cosmic Care and Covenant Particularity.</b> Ps 147 has a distinctive three-movement structure, each beginning with a praise summons: 'Praise the LORD!' (v1), 'Sing to the LORD with thanksgiving' (v7), 'Praise the LORD, O Jerusalem!' (v12). The psalm's theological genius is its juxtaposition of the cosmic (YHWH determines the number of the stars, v4) with the intimate (YHWH heals the brokenhearted, v3) — the same God who maintains the stellar order also counts and names each star and each wound. The closing verses (vv19-20) make explicit that YHWH's word and statutes belong particularly to Israel — a universal creation-theology climaxing in covenant particularity. 'Praise the LORD! For it is good to sing praises to our God; for it is pleasant, and a song of praise is fitting' — the triple justification for praise: good (<i>ki tov</i>), pleasant (<i>ki naim</i>), fitting (<i>tehillah navah</i>).</p>", "2": "<p><b>'The LORD builds up Jerusalem; he gathers the outcasts of Israel'</b> — 'builds up Jerusalem' (<i>YHWH boneh Yerushalaim</i>) — the post-exilic return as divine city-building: YHWH himself is the builder who restores what the Babylonians destroyed (cf. Ps 51:18; Neh 2:17-18). 'Gathers the outcasts of Israel' (<i>nidchei Yisrael yekanneys</i>) — the scattered diaspora gathered: the technical term <i>nidach</i> (the outcast/banished) refers to those expelled from the land (Deut 30:4; Isa 11:12; 56:8). The Psalm's opening establishes the post-exilic context: YHWH is actively rebuilding and regathering.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'He heals the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds'</b> — 'heals the brokenhearted' (<i>harophe lishvure lev</i>) — YHWH as the divine physician of interior wounds: not the wounds of battle but the wounds of grief, exile, loss. 'Binds up their wounds' (<i>umechabesh le'atzeivotam</i>) — the bandaging (<i>chabash</i>) of wounds is the medical image: careful, attentive binding. The same God who gathers the scattered exiles (v2) also heals the interior damage that exile has caused. The verse bridges the national (regathering) and the personal (healing) dimensions of restoration.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'He determines the number of the stars; he gives to all of them their names'</b> — 'determines the number of the stars' (<i>moneh mispar lakochavim</i>) — YHWH counts the uncountable: the ancient Near East saw the stars as beyond human enumeration (Gen 15:5: 'Look toward heaven, and number the stars, if you are able to number them'). 'Gives to all of them their names' (<i>lekullam shemot yiqra</i>) — naming as an act of sovereignty (Gen 2:19-20: Adam named the animals as an expression of human dominion over creation). YHWH's naming of every star establishes his sovereign knowledge of every created thing. The same God who numbers and names every star also counts and knows every wound (v3).</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Great is our Lord, and abundant in power; his understanding is beyond measure'</b> — 'abundant in power' (<i>rav koach</i>) — the greatness of YHWH is measured in power — not the abstract omnipotence of philosophy but the covenant power demonstrated in Exodus, conquest, and return from exile. 'His understanding is beyond measure' (<i>litevunato ein mispar</i>, his understanding has no number) — in contrast to the stars whose number YHWH knows (v4), YHWH's own understanding is innumerable, incalculable. The asymmetry is the point: what YHWH counts cannot count YHWH.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'The LORD lifts up the humble; he casts the wicked to the ground'</b> — the divine reversal formula (cf. Pss 113:7-8; 1 Sam 2:7-8): the humble (<i>anavim</i>) lifted, the wicked (<i>resha'im</i>) cast down. The <i>anavim</i> (the poor, humble, meek) are the characteristic recipients of divine grace throughout the Psalter (Pss 9:12; 22:26; 37:11; 149:4). The reversal is not a general principle but a covenant promise: YHWH has aligned himself with the humble.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Sing to the LORD with thanksgiving; make melody to our God on the lyre!'</b> — the second movement begins: <i>anu laYHWH betodah</i> (sing/answer to YHWH with thanksgiving). The <i>todah</i> (thanksgiving) vocabulary connects to the thanksgiving sacrifice (cf. Ps 116:17) — music as the vocal complement to the sacrificial act. The lyre (<i>kinnor</i>) was the primary instrument of Levitical praise (1 Chr 25:1-6; Ps 33:2).</p>", "8": "<p><b>'He covers the heavens with clouds; he prepares rain for the earth; he makes grass grow on the hills'</b> — the creation-care sequence: clouds → rain → grass. The hydrological cycle as divine providence. Elijah's prayer for rain (1 Kgs 18:41-45) and the covenant blessings of Lev 26:4 and Deut 28:12 establish rain as the most fundamental sign of YHWH's active provision. The grass on the hills is the ultimate beneficiary — the transformation from bare hill to covered pasture through divine precipitation.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'He gives to the beasts their food, and to the young ravens that cry'</b> — 'young ravens that cry' (<i>livenei orev asher yiqra'u</i>) — the young ravens' cry is answered by divine provision (Job 38:41: 'Who provides for the raven its prey, when its young ones cry to God?'). The raven was an unclean bird (Lev 11:15), ritually excluded from Israel's sacrificial system — yet YHWH provides for it. Jesus echoes this in Luke 12:24 ('Consider the ravens: they neither sow nor reap, they have neither storehouse nor barn, and yet God feeds them').</p>", "10": "<p><b>'His delight is not in the strength of the horse, nor his pleasure in the legs of a man'</b> — YHWH's non-delight in military power: 'the strength of the horse' (<i>koach hassus</i>) — the warhorse as the supreme symbol of military might (Pss 20:7; 33:17; Isa 31:1). 'Nor his pleasure in the legs of a man' (<i>shiqei haish</i>) — human athletic or military prowess. The contrast with vv8-9: YHWH delights in feeding ravens, not in equipping armies. The covenant military theology: Israel's security comes from covenant trust, not from cavalry (Deut 17:16: the king was prohibited from multiplying horses).</p>", "11": "<p><b>'But the LORD takes pleasure in those who fear him, in those who hope in his steadfast love'</b> — the positive counterpart to v10: YHWH's delight (<i>rotzeh</i>) is in 'those who fear him' (<i>yare'av</i>) and 'those who hope in his steadfast love' (<i>hameyachalim lechasdo</i>). Two covenant postures: fear (the covenant reverence of Ps 111:10) and hope in <i>chesed</i> (the trust that YHWH's loyal love will prove reliable). These are what YHWH values more than military hardware.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Praise the LORD, O Jerusalem! Praise your God, O Zion!'</b> — the third movement: 'Praise the LORD, O Jerusalem!' (<i>shabchi YHWH Yerushalaim</i>) — the city itself summoned to praise. Zion and Jerusalem are addressed as if they are covenant partners capable of worship. The personification of the city as worshiper reflects the prophetic tradition (Isa 40:9; 52:1-2; 54:1) of addressing Zion as a person whose fortunes have changed.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'For he strengthens the bars of your gates; he blesses your children within you'</b> — 'strengthens the bars of your gates' (<i>ki chizeq berichei she'arayich</i>) — the city's gate-bars are the primary urban defense mechanism in the ancient world. YHWH as the one who fortifies them. 'Blesses your children within you' (<i>berach banayich beqirbech</i>) — the blessing of the next generation within the secure city. The physical security (gate-bars) and the biological future (children) are both YHWH's gift.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'He makes peace in your borders; he fills you with the finest of the wheat'</b> — 'peace in your borders' (<i>hasam gevulech shalom</i>) — the covenant blessing of Lev 26:6 ('I will give peace in the land') applied to post-exilic Jerusalem. 'The finest of the wheat' (<i>chelev chittim yasbiech</i>) — the fat/best of the wheat: the covenant abundance that Ps 81:16 promised ('I would feed you with the finest of the wheat'). Peace and abundance are paired covenant blessings.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'He sends out his command to the earth; his word runs swiftly'</b> — 'his word runs swiftly' (<i>ad-mehera yaruts devaro</i>) — the divine Word personified as a swift messenger. The creation-by-word theology (Gen 1; Ps 33:6,9: 'he spoke and it came to be') is now applied to ongoing governance: YHWH's commands continue to run through the created order, maintaining it. Isa 55:11 ('my word that goes out from my mouth shall not return to me empty') develops this theme. John 1:1-14 (the Word who 'was God' and 'became flesh') takes the personification of the divine word to its christological culmination.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'He gives snow like wool; he scatters frost like ashes'</b> — the winter weather phenomena as divine actions: snow 'like wool' (<i>hakkefar kaefer</i>) — the visual comparison of white snow to white wool fleece. Frost 'like ashes' (<i>kepher kaepher yefazer</i>) — the scattered appearance of frost across a surface. These meteorological phenomena are not accidents of nature but YHWH's active sending. Isa 1:18 uses 'white as snow' as the image of divine forgiveness.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'He hurls down his crystals of ice like crumbs; who can stand before his cold?'</b> — 'crystals of ice like crumbs' (<i>karcho kephitim yashlich</i>) — hail or ice-pellets thrown like bread-crumbs. 'Who can stand before his cold?' (<i>liphnei qarato mi ya'amod</i>) — the rhetorical question: no creature can withstand the divine cold. The natural world's extremes are expressions of YHWH's sovereign power, applied to praise rather than threat.</p>", "18": "<p><b>'He sends out his word and melts them; he makes his wind blow and the waters flow'</b> — the reversal: 'sends out his word and melts them' (<i>yishlach devaro veyamsem</i>) — the same divine word that sent the snow (v16) and ice (v17) now melts them. 'His wind blow and the waters flow' (<i>yashev rucho yizzelu mayim</i>) — the spring thaw as divine word: when YHWH speaks, the frozen season ends. The <i>ruach</i> (wind/spirit) of YHWH that moved over the primordial waters (Gen 1:2) now moves over the ice to produce flow.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'He declares his word to Jacob, his statutes and rules to Israel'</b> — the transition from creation (vv4-18) to covenant: 'declares his word to Jacob' (<i>magid devarav leYaakov</i>) — the same divine Word (<i>dabar</i>) that runs through creation (v15) and melts the ice (v18) is also the Torah given to Israel. The covenant people receive the creative word as their law. The equation of creation-word and covenant-word is explicit: Torah is not separate from creation but the same divine speech applied to the covenant community's life.</p>", "20": "<p><b>'He has not dealt thus with any other nation; they do not know his rules. Praise the LORD!'</b> — the psalm's climax: the particularism that the universal creation-theology leads to. 'He has not dealt thus with any other nation' (<i>lo asah chen lechol goy</i>) — YHWH's self-disclosure through law and covenant is Israel's unique privilege. No other nation has the Torah. 'They do not know his rules' (<i>umishpatim bal yeda'um</i>) — the nations' ignorance is not contemptible but simply factual: the covenant statutes are Israel's inheritance alone. The Psalm that opened with universal praise (vv1-6) closes with the covenant's particularity: creation is universal; covenant is particular. The 'Hallelujah' returns.</p>"}, "148": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 148: Cosmic Praise Psalm — All Creation Called to Worship.</b> Ps 148 is the most comprehensive summons to universal praise in the Psalter. It moves in two concentric sweeps: the heavenly realm (vv1-6) then the earthly realm (vv7-12), before closing with the covenant community's praise (vv13-14). Every stratum of creation is addressed: angels, sun, moon, stars, waters above the heavens (v4), sea monsters and deeps (v7), weather phenomena (v8), mountains and hills and trees (v9), animals (v10), kings and peoples (v11), young and old (v12). The psalm has a structural parallel with Ps 8 and Dan 3:57-88 (the Benedicite). 'Praise the LORD from the heavens; praise him in the heights!' — the twofold directive opens the heavenly summons: <i>halelu YHWH min hashamayim</i> (from the heavens) and <i>halleluhu bamromim</i> (in the heights/exalted places).</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Praise him, all his angels; praise him, all his hosts!'</b> — the heavenly council summoned: 'all his angels' (<i>kol-malachav</i>) and 'all his hosts' (<i>kol-tzeva'av</i>). The 'hosts' (<i>tzeva</i>) are the heavenly army — the divine council of Ps 82, the armies of heaven (1 Kgs 22:19; Job 1-2). In Ps 103:20-21 the angels are summoned to praise; here they are the first in the cosmic choir. Rev 5:11-14 depicts the same concentric circle of heavenly beings joining the universal doxology.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Praise him, sun and moon; praise him, all you shining stars!'</b> — the luminaries of Gen 1:14-19 summoned. The sun, moon, and stars were the objects of worship in surrounding cultures (Deut 4:19; 17:3; Ezek 8:16 — the sun-worshipers at the temple's east gate). Ps 148 subverts the astral religion: the objects of Gentile worship are called to worship YHWH. They are not divine beings but praising creatures.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Praise him, you highest heavens, and you waters above the heavens!'</b> — 'highest heavens' (<i>shemei hashamayim</i>, the heaven of heavens) — the uppermost cosmological stratum (Deut 10:14; 1 Kgs 8:27). 'Waters above the heavens' (<i>hammayim asher meal hashamayim</i>) — the waters above the firmament of Gen 1:7: in the ancient Near Eastern cosmology, the sky-dome held back an upper ocean whose sluice-gates opened to produce rain (Gen 7:11: 'the windows of the heavens were opened'). These cosmic waters are also summoned to praise.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Let them praise the name of the LORD! For he commanded and they were created'</b> — the ground of heavenly praise: creation by divine command. 'He commanded and they were created' (<i>ki hu tzivah venivre'u</i>) — the fiat-creation of Gen 1 ('and God said... and it was so'). The imperative form ('let them praise') applies even to inanimate heavenly bodies: they exist by command and their existence is praise. Existence itself is the response to the creative word.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'And he established them forever and ever; he gave a decree, and it shall not pass away'</b> — 'established them forever' (<i>vaya'amideim laad leolam</i>) — the created order's permanence by divine decree. 'A decree and it shall not pass away' (<i>choq natan velo ya'avor</i>) — the cosmos operates by YHWH's <i>choq</i> (statute/ordinance): the same word as covenant law. Creation is law-governed; the laws of nature are covenant-like decrees that do not lapse. Jer 33:25-26 uses this same 'covenant with the day and night' as the ground for the covenant with David's descendants.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Praise the LORD from the earth, you great sea creatures and all deeps'</b> — the earthly summons begins. 'Great sea creatures' (<i>tanninim</i>) — the great sea-dragons or sea monsters of the deep. In Canaanite mythology (<i>Ugaritic</i>: <i>Lotan</i>; Babylonian: <i>Tiamat</i>), these were the primordial chaos-forces that the storm-god defeated in creation. Ps 148 recruits them as praisers: what pagan myth describes as divine opponents, the Psalter presents as creaturely worshipers. 'All deeps' (<i>kol tehomot</i>) — the abyssal waters, the <i>tehom</i> of Gen 1:2.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Fire and hail, snow and mist; stormy wind fulfilling his word!'</b> — the weather phenomena as praisers — and as YHWH's agents: 'fulfilling his word' (<i>oseh devaro</i>) — the storms execute the divine word. Ps 147:15-18 developed the same theology: the weather is YHWH's instrument of governance. 'Fire' (<i>esh</i>) — lightning; 'hail' (<i>barad</i>) — the Exodus plague weapon (Exod 9:18-26); 'snow' and 'mist' (<i>sheleg veqitor</i>) — the full range of precipitative phenomena.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'Mountains and all hills, fruit trees and all cedars!'</b> — the terrestrial topography and vegetation: mountains (<i>harim</i>) and hills (<i>geva'ot</i>), fruit trees (<i>etz peri</i>) and cedars (<i>kol arzim</i>). The cedars of Lebanon were the most majestic trees of the ancient world (Ps 29:5; Isa 2:13). By including the cedars alongside fruit trees, the psalm encompasses both the useful and the awe-inspiring, the cultivated and the wild.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'Beasts and all livestock, creeping things and flying birds!'</b> — the animal kingdom: 'beasts' (<i>chayah</i>) — wild animals; 'livestock' (<i>behemah</i>) — domesticated animals; 'creeping things' (<i>remes</i>) — the crawling creatures of Gen 1:24-25; 'flying birds' (<i>tzippor kanaf</i>) — all avian life. The four-fold animal catalogue corresponds to the categories of Gen 1:24-25. Creation inverts the direction of Gen 1 (creation moving from heavens to earth to creatures) into a comprehensive doxology moving from creatures back toward the Creator.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'Kings of the earth and all peoples, princes and all rulers of the earth!'</b> — the human realm: 'kings of the earth' (<i>malchei eretz</i>) and 'all peoples' (<i>kol-leumim</i>) — the political and ethnic scope. Princes (<i>sarim</i>) and rulers (<i>shophetei aretz</i>). The political powers that claim ultimate allegiance are here relativized: they are creatures among creatures, summoned to praise the one true King. The connection to Ps 2 (kings who rage against YHWH) and to the eschatological vision of Rev 21:24 (kings bringing glory into the New Jerusalem).</p>", "12": "<p><b>'Young men and maidens together, old men and children!'</b> — the full human demographic: 'young men and maidens' (<i>bachurim vegam betulot</i>), 'old men and children' (<i>zeqenim im-ne'arim</i>). No age or gender excluded from the praise. The Hallel's universal vision includes every human category within the covenant community's doxology. Joel 2:28-29 (young men visions, old men dreams, sons and daughters prophesying) draws on the same comprehensive inclusion.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'Let them praise the name of the LORD, for his name alone is exalted; his majesty is above earth and heaven'</b> — 'his name alone is exalted' (<i>ki-nisgav shemo levado</i>) — the exclusive elevation of the divine Name: no other name can be set alongside YHWH's. 'His majesty is above earth and heaven' (<i>hodo al eretz veshamayim</i>) — the divine glory surpasses both the earthly realm (vv7-12) and the heavenly realm (vv1-6) that the psalm has just called to praise. YHWH is above the very creation he summons.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'He has raised up a horn for his people, praise for all his saints, for the people of Israel who are near to him. Praise the LORD!'</b> — the cosmic praise psalm ends with covenant particularity. 'Raised up a horn for his people' (<i>vayarem qeren le'amo</i>) — the horn as symbol of national strength and dignity: YHWH has exalted Israel's power. 'The people of Israel who are near to him' (<i>am qerovo</i>) — the covenant nearness of Israel: while all creation praises (vv1-13), Israel is the people uniquely close to YHWH. The concentric circles of vv1-14 end at the innermost circle: the covenant community that is YHWH's.</p>"}, "149": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 149: New Song, Two-Edged Sword — Praise and Eschatological Judgment.</b> Ps 149 is the most tension-filled of the five final Hallelujah psalms. It pairs the worship assembly's joy (vv1-5) with their role as YHWH's agents of judgment (vv6-9), holding praise and divine warrior imagery together. The 'new song' (<i>shir chadash</i>) appears in Pss 33:3; 40:3; 96:1; 98:1; 144:9 and Rev 5:9; 14:3 — it is the song of unprecedented divine deliverance. 'Praise the LORD! Sing to the LORD a new song, his praise in the assembly of the godly!' — the 'assembly of the godly' (<i>qehal chasidim</i>) — the covenant-loyal ones (<i>chasidim</i>, from <i>chesed</i>) as the specific worshiping community. Their assembly is the setting for the new song.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Let Israel be glad in his Maker; let the children of Zion rejoice in their King!'</b> — 'glad in his Maker' (<i>yismach Yisrael beosav</i>) — the creator-creature joy: Israel's gladness is in the one who made them. 'Rejoice in their King' (<i>yigilu venei Tzion beMalkam</i>) — the children of Zion (the covenant community in Jerusalem) rejoice in YHWH as their king. The Davidic-YHWH kingship theology: YHWH is Israel's true king whose human representative is the Davidic king (1 Sam 8:7: 'they have not rejected you, but they have rejected me from being king over them').</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Let them praise his name with dancing, making melody to him with tambourine and lyre!'</b> — dance (<i>machol</i>) and the tambourine (<i>toph</i>) — the most festive, embodied form of worship. The dancing praise of Miriam at the sea (Exod 15:20) and David before the ark (2 Sam 6:14) are the biblical models. Praise that is fully embodied, not merely verbal or mental. The lyre (<i>kinnor</i>) provides the harmonic complement to the percussive tambourine.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'For the LORD takes pleasure in his people; he adorns the humble with salvation'</b> — 'takes pleasure in his people' (<i>ki rotze YHWH beamo</i>) — the divine delight in the covenant community (cf. Ps 147:11: YHWH's pleasure in those who fear him). 'Adorns the humble with salvation' (<i>yephaer anavim beyeshu'ah</i>) — the <i>anavim</i> (humble/meek) receive salvation (<i>yeshu'ah</i>) as adornment (<i>pe'er</i>, beauty/glory): their salvation is not merely rescue but transformation into beauty. The <i>anavim</i> were the Beatitude-people ('blessed are the meek') before the NT; Ps 149 is their promised adornment.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Let the godly exult in glory; let them sing for joy on their beds'</b> — 'sing for joy on their beds' (<i>yirannenu al-mishkevotam</i>) — the intimate dimension of praise: even in the private resting place, even at night, the <i>chasidim</i> sing. The contrast with the public assembly (v1) and the battle (vv6-9): praise penetrates every setting, private and public, peaceful and combative.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Let the high praises of God be in their throats and two-edged swords in their hands'</b> — the most striking verse of the psalm: the union of worship and warfare. 'High praises of God' (<i>romemot El bigeronam</i>) — exaltations of God in their throats: the same organ that produces praise also breathes battle. 'Two-edged swords' (<i>cherev piphiyot</i>) in their hands simultaneously. The combination has both historical and eschatological dimensions: Nehemiah's wall-builders held a tool in one hand and a weapon in the other (Neh 4:17); the eschatological army praises as it fights.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'...to execute vengeance on the nations and punishments on the peoples'</b> — 'execute vengeance on the nations' (<i>la'asot neqamah bagoyim tochechot bale'umim</i>) — the covenant warrior language: YHWH's vengeance (<i>neqamah</i>) executed through the covenant people's action. The OT understanding of holy war: Israel as the instrument of divine judgment on nations that have accumulated covenant-violating sins (Gen 15:16: 'the iniquity of the Amorites is not yet complete'). Paul redefines this warfare as spiritual in Eph 6:10-18 and 2 Cor 10:4.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'...to bind their kings with chains and their nobles with fetters of iron'</b> — 'bind their kings with chains' (<i>le'esor malkeihem biziqim venichbadeihem bekhavle barzel</i>) — the political dimension of the divine warrior victory: the kings and nobles who have defied YHWH's sovereignty will be bound. The iron chains echo both the Egyptian bondage of Israel (which YHWH broke) and the Assyrian-Babylonian captivity of Israel's kings (which YHWH allowed). The reversal: those who held others captive are themselves bound.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'...to execute on them the judgment written! This is honor for all his godly ones. Praise the LORD!'</b> — 'the judgment written' (<i>hamishpat katuv</i>) — the pre-written judgment: the execution of what YHWH has decreed in his heavenly law. The book-of-judgment imagery (Dan 7:10; Rev 20:12) — YHWH's decrees are not improvised but enacted from prior written record. 'Honor for all his godly ones' (<i>hadar hu lechol chasidav</i>) — the final paradox: participating in the divine judgment is itself the dignity of the <i>chasidim</i>. The closing 'Hallelujah!' holds the paradox: praise and judgment are not opposites in the Psalter's theology.</p>"}, "150": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 150: The Grand Doxology — Conclusion of the Psalter.</b> Ps 150 is the Psalter's conclusion: a pure, undiluted doxology that answers the Psalter's five lament books with a final, sustained, instrument-by-instrument praise. There is no petition, no lament, no narrative — only the summons to praise, the location of praise, the reason for praise, and the means of praise. The number of imperative verbs in vv1-5 is debated but significant: 10-13 'praises' summons, corresponding perhaps to the Ten Commandments or the Decalogue's call to covenant relationship. 'Praise the LORD! Praise God in his sanctuary; praise him in his mighty heavens!' — 'his sanctuary' (<i>miqdosho</i>) and 'his mighty heavens' (<i>raqia uzzo</i>) — the two locations of praise: the earthly temple (the specific locus of Israel's worship) and the heavenly firmament (the cosmic arena). The earthly and heavenly dimensions of worship are both valid.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Praise him for his mighty deeds; praise him according to his excellent greatness!'</b> — the two grounds for praise: 'his mighty deeds' (<i>gevurotav</i>) — the acts of divine power in history (Exodus, Conquest, Return from exile); 'his excellent greatness' (<i>kegodol tuvo</i>) — his intrinsic greatness, independent of any specific act. The acts reveal the character; the character grounds the acts. Both are proper grounds for praise: what YHWH has done (salvation history) and who YHWH is (divine nature).</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Praise him with trumpet sound; praise him with lute and harp!'</b> — the instrument catalogue begins. 'Trumpet' (<i>shofar</i>) — the ram's horn, the instrument of covenant assembly (Lev 23:24; Num 10:10), of the Jubilee proclamation (Lev 25:9), and of Sinai theophany (Exod 19:16). 'Lute' (<i>nevel</i>) and 'harp' (<i>kinnor</i>) — the stringed instruments of Levitical praise (1 Chr 25:1-7). The trumpet's commanding sound is joined by the lyrical strings: proclamation and melody together.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Praise him with tambourine and dance; praise him with strings and pipe!'</b> — 'tambourine and dance' (<i>toph umachol</i>) — the percussion and physical movement of embodied worship (cf. Ps 149:3; Miriam's dance, Exod 15:20; David's dance, 2 Sam 6:14). 'Strings and pipe' (<i>minim veuggav</i>) — further stringed instruments and the wind instrument (<i>uggav</i>, possibly a flute or pan-pipe). The full range of instrumental timbre: percussion, strings, wind, and bodily movement — worship employing every physical faculty.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Praise him with sounding cymbals; praise him with loud clashing cymbals!'</b> — 'sounding cymbals' (<i>tziltzalei shama</i>) and 'loud clashing cymbals' (<i>tziltzalei teru'ah</i>) — two varieties of cymbal: one ringing, one crashing. The cymbals were part of the Levitical orchestra (1 Chr 13:8; 15:16,19,28; 16:5). The final instrument is the loudest, most percussive: the Psalter's doxology crescendos rather than fades. Paul's famous 'noisy gong or clanging cymbal' (1 Cor 13:1) uses this verse's vocabulary to describe love-less speech — the cymbal's noise without love's content is empty, but in Ps 150 the cymbals have their proper context.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'Let everything that has breath praise the LORD! Praise the LORD!'</b> — the Psalter's final word: 'everything that has breath' (<i>kol haneshama tehalel Yah</i>). The <i>neshamah</i> (breath) — the breath of life that YHWH breathed into Adam (Gen 2:7: 'he breathed into his nostrils the breath of life'). Every creature possessing the breath of God is called to return praise to God. The Psalter that began with 'Blessed is the man' (Ps 1:1) and moved through 150 psalms of lament, praise, wisdom, and doxology ends at the universal: every breathing creature is summoned to praise. The final 'Hallelujah!' is simultaneously the end of the Psalter and an opening — the praise that cannot be concluded.</p>"}}

